<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="section-2" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Functions</title>

  <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Understanding how the starter code works</p></li>
      <li><p>Identify function definitions, <c>setup</c>, <c>draw</c></p></li>
      <li><p>Identify function calls, <c>createCanvas</c>, <c>background</c></p></li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <subsection>
    <title>Starter Code</title>    
    <p>
      Each time you make a new p5 program you will get the starter code shown below.
    </p>
  
    <program language="javascript">
    <![CDATA[
    function setup() {
      createCanvas(400, 400);
    }

    function draw() {
      background(220);
    }
    ]]>
    </program>

    <p>
      When you press the play button, p5 executes the setup function and the single statement within
      setup's curly braces, <c>createCanvas(400, 400)</c>, is executed.
    </p> 

    <p>
      Next, the draw function is executed and the statement contained with it's curly braces,
      <c>background(220)</c> is executed. The background function is executed repeatedly, but since 
      there are no changes to the canvas, you will not notice this is happening. We sometimes refer 
      to the draw function as the draw loop.
    </p>
  </subsection>

<subsection>
  <title>Syntax</title>

  <p>
    Imagine the following situation. You write an essay, then turn it into your English teacher. They read your 
    essay, locate and markup the first grammar mistake, then hand the paper back to you. You correct
    this mistake and resubmit the essay. This process continues until there are no more grammar mistakes in your
    paper. Then, and only then, does your teacher read your essay for it's content.
  </p>

  <p>
    Writing a computer program is very much like the process above. Fortunately, a computer language's grammar, 
    called syntax, is simpler than those of natural languages, such as English, French, Chinese, and Spanish. 
    When a syntax error occurs, the computer will state which rule was broken and approximate its location. 
    Learning to decipher these messages takes practice. Keep in mind that a program must be completely free of 
    syntax errors before it can execute.
  </p>
</subsection>

<subsection> 
  <title>Function Definitions</title>

  <p>
    There are two types of functions in js, those that return values, like <m>f(x)</m> 
    in math, and those that don't return a value. We will mostly focus on writing 
    function definitions that don't return values. You can think of a function definition as a 
    container; it holds a block of code that runs whenever you call that function.
  </p>

  <p>
    To write a function definition, you must include all of the parts, 
    in the correct order, for the definition to be syntactically correct.
  </p>

  <p>Below are the syntax rules for a function definition:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><p>Starts with the word <c>function</c></p></li>
    <li><p>Then the name of the function</p></li>
    <li><p>Followed by a pair of parentheses<c>()</c>, which may or may not contain one or more 
      items between them</p></li>
    <li><p>A left curly brace, <c>{</c></p></li>
    <li><p>Finally, a closing right curly brace<c>}</c></p></li>
  </ul>

  <p>An example of a function definition</p>

  <program language="javascript">
    <![CDATA[
    function functionName() {
    }
    ]]>
  </program>

  <p>
    The closing right curly brace may look a bit odd being alone on the next line, but
    as we will see in the next example, it will have one or more statements before it.
  </p> 

  <p>
    There are two <term>function definitions</term> in the code window: setup and draw.
    Note, while not necessary for js to understand your program, we indent all the code 
    between the line that has the word function and the right curly brace.
  </p>

  <program language="javascript">
    <![CDATA[
      function setup() {
         createCanvas(400, 400);
      }

      function draw() {
         background(220);
      }
   ]]>
  </program>    

 
</subsection>

<subsection>
  <title>Function Calls</title>

  <p>
    The statement inside the setup function, <c>createCanvas</c>, is a <term>function call</term>. 
    It contains two arguments which specify the width and height of the canvas in pixels.
  </p>

  <figure xml:id="canvas_height_lessthan_width">
    <caption>In this example, the second argument was changed to 200, so now, the width is twice the height.</caption>
    <image source="images/changeCanvasHeight.png" width="80%"/>    
  </figure>
  
  <p>
    <c>createCanvas(400,400)</c> is a <term>function call</term>. It calls a built-in function 
     from the p5 library. It has two arguments inside it's parentheses, 400 and 400.
     The first argument makes a canvas that is 400 <term>pixels</term> wide and 400 
     <term>pixels</term> tall. As you recall, it is the gray square to the right of the 
     code window. 
  </p>

  <p>MCQ WHAT IS THE OTHER FUNCTION CALL IN THIS PROGRAM?</p>
  <p>MCQ WHAT IS THE ARGUMENT TO THIS FUNCTION CALL?</p>   

  <p>
    For the following, the canvas will appear <alert>below</alert> the code window, which 
    is different from the p5 editor
  </p>

 <program xml:id="p5js-modify-starter-code" interactive="activecode" language="html">

    <preamble visible="no">
      <![CDATA[<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <script src="external/p5.min.js"></script>
</head>
<body>]]>
    </preamble>

    <code>
<![CDATA[<script>

  function setup() {
    createCanvas(400, 300);
  }

  function draw() {
    background(220);
  }
  
</script>]]>
    </code>

  </program>

  <p>Arguments are separated by commas, so the number of commas will always be one less than
     the number of arguments.    </p>
  </subsection>   

  <subsection>
    <title>Exercises</title>
    <exercise label="function_definition" language="javascript">
      <title>Mixed-up Code Example</title>
      <statement>
          <p>Rearrange the blocks to correctly define the function.</p>
      </statement>
      <blocks layout="horizontal">
          <block order="1"><c>function</c></block>
          <block order="2"><c>foo</c></block>
          <block order="3"><c>(</c></block>
          <block order="4"><c>)</c></block>
          <block order="5"><c>{</c></block>
          <block order="6"><c>}</c></block>  
      </blocks>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>Which are examples of function definitions?</p>
      </statement>
      <choices randomize="yes">
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>setup and createCanvas</p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>Incorrect. One of these is a function definition and the other is a function call.</p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>

        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement>
            <p>setup and draw</p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>
              Correct! Both of these are preceded by the <term>reserved word</term>, function, and 
              meet the syntactic requirements.
            </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>

        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>draw and background</p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>No. One of these is a function definition and the other is a function call.</p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>

        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>createCanvas and background</p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>Incorrect. Neither is preceded by the word function.</p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
      </choices>
</exercise>
  </subsection>
</section>